Elucidatorium] Froben‘s edition, published in Aug. 1517, is a reprint of the first. Paris, H. Stephanus, 19 Apr. 1516. The contents of the book are given in the next sentence.

Clithtouei] Josse Clicthove (e. 1472—22 Sept. 1543), of Nieuport‚ in Flanders. He went to Paris, c. 1488, and was a pupil first of Chas. Fernand and then of Faber Stapulensis, to whom be became attached (cf. Ep. 597. 13 n.) and many of whose books he after- wards edited. After becoming Fellow of the Sorbonne, c, 1499 and D.D. 1506, lie resided at Cluny as tutor to the Abbot’s nephews. Then, 1513-7, he was in Paris as tutor to the young Bp. of Tournay, L. Guillard (Ep. 360. 18 n.); whose fortunes he thencesorward fol- lowed, receiving a benefice at Tournay in 1519, and c. 1525 a canonry at Char- tres, which he held until his death.

He wrote and edited numerous works, educational and theological. Many of the latter being against Luther, he was invited to, and took a prominent part in, the Synod of Paris, 1528.

See Bibl. Belyica, Ghent. 1888, and a thesis by J. A. Clerval‚ 1894.
